<br>
I guess i should also clarify what i mean about the eikaiwa thing.  english teaching isn't bad - at first it seems like a pretty good deal - 200000 yen a month to do nothing more than sit in a classroom and repeat &quot;hello, my name is ...&quot; to a bunch of students.  Until you begin to realize that *that is all you'll ever be allowed to do* if you don't have any other skills and are not fluent in japanese.  And that 200000 yen is really a pretty cr@ppy salary... and that no matter how many conjunctions or whatnot you teach your students (provided they even want to learn ) you're not going to get a raise...ever. and that you'll be treated like a disposable asset (which you will be) and dumped as soon as your employer feels like it, and treated like garbage the rest of the time (&quot;vacation&quot; --- HAH!  No vacation for you!  you work 72 hours this week without overtime or you're fired!!) (lol can you tell i've have friends that've worked for Nova?).  <br>
