ent on learning and working with. that is the main reason i was thinking of a college in japan.  <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#CCCCCC><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub25.ezboard.com/bpolykarbonbbs.showUserPublicProfile?gid=maimaipanda>maimaipanda</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Resident Panda</span><br> <font color=#336699>(4/14/03 12:55 pm)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub25.ezboard.com/fpolykarbonbbsfrm5.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=1086.topic&index=8>Reply</a>   <BR><img src=http://www.sit.wisc.edu/~mamiller2/temp/pandatea.jpg height=146 width=130></td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: trying to move to japan</span><hr size=1> hey higa,<br>
<br>
my previous comments certainly shouldn't be taken as an indictment against <!--EZCODE ITALIC START--><em>all</em><!--EZCODE ITALIC END--> japanese colleges!  There are many excellent world-class universities in Japan, including Tokyo, Waseda, Kyoto and so forth.  At the same time, the demands on the average Japanese college student are incredibly low relative to what American colleges require.  In Japan, less emphasis tends to be placed on one's actual education and more on the &quot;name&quot; of the college in conjunction with &quot;on the job training&quot; specific to each company.<br>
<br>
You had mentioned you wanted to be an illustrator - I'm not an expert in this field by any stretch, but for such a proffession, you would end up going to a senmongakko (like a &quot;vocational&quot; or &quot;trade school&quot;; i might have gotten the word wrong) as opposed to a college proper.  I have no idea about the state of Japanese vocational schools or how easy/difficult it is to get into them, etc.  You will need to ask Raku or Aoh or some other native Japanese about that...<br>
<br>
What I will caution you on (I know it seems like I am doing nothing but dumping water on your parade! sorry!) is that Japan is an extremely closed society.  It is extremely difficult for foreigners to gain acceptance and entrance into the &quot;normal&quot; strata of Japanese society, and this includes, of course, working for a Japanese company as a &quot;normal&quot; employee. (Most foreigners employed in Japan are employed in the Japanese branches of foreign companies, and generally are there only as temporary transfers, furthermore their tasks are usually highly specialized and usually involve doing something with english; it is extremely rare for a foreigner to be hired and employed in a fashion similar to a regular Japanese citizen - and if your japanese is not 100% fluent, *forget it*).  This underlying discrimination unfortunately extends even to &quot;hafu&quot;, children who are half-Japanese.  The fact that your Japanese is not 100% fluent will only harm you... being hafu versus being a full blooded gaijin only means that they won't automatically bust out the picture menus and the panicky broken english when you walk into McDonalds - but when it comes to trying to do anything of actual substance, you and the rest of the white gaijin are stuck in the same permanently &quot;foreigner&quot; boat.  What I'm trying to get across is that your possibilities of being hired as an anime/manga artist in Japan are very very slim.  They have an overabundance of highly talented domestic artists already, and when you factor in the closed nature of the society, it doesn't seem like a very optomistic picture..<br>
[EDIT]: I should clarify - 'normal' &quot;hafu&quot; are not discriminated against to the extent which white foreigners are.  I was referring to &quot;hafu&quot; who were born and raised in America, and don't speak Japanese fluently in my discussion above.<br>
<br>
I'm not trying to rail on Japanese society (it is what it is, for better or for worse, same as the rest of the world) nor rain on your parade, I just want you to have as good a picture of what you're up against when you set out on this course of action, so you can prepare yourself as best you can in the time you have left.  <br>
<br>
